Then, if pqmax's size is larger than pqmin's, move one element from pqmax to pqmin. So after processing, the sizes can only differ by at most 1. But the Java code's rebalancing steps:

After inserting into one of the heaps, it checks: if (pqmin.size() > pqmax.size()) {
    move top of pqmin to pqmax.
}

Then, if (pqmin.size() < pqmax.size()) {
    move top of pqmax to pqmin.
} Wait, after moving from pqmin to pqmax, pqmax's size increases by one, pqmin's decreases by one.

Wait, the code as written does these steps once each. So perhaps the code is not handling all cases, but in practice, after the first move, the second condition may require another move. Wait, let's look at the Java code again:

if (pqmin.size() > pqmax.size()) {
    sumMax += pqmin.peek();
    sumMin -= pqmin.peek();
    pqmax.add(pqmin.poll());
}
if (pqmin.size() < pqmax.size()) {
    sumMax -= pqmax.peek();
    sumMin += pqmax.peek();
    pqmin.add(pqmax.poll());
} Wait, so after the first if block (moving from pqmin to pqmax), then the second if block checks if pqmin.size < pqmax.size.
